04243nam a22005535i 9780226413426DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016028700  a97802264134267 a10.7208/97802264134262doi  a(DE-B1597)550039  a(OCoLC)1139875648  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHQ76.3.U52bI4466 2017 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aOrne, Jason, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBoystown :bSex and Community in Chicago /cJason Orne. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b29 halftones, 1 line drawing  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Nightfall -- t2. On Safari -- t3. Naked Intimacy -- t4. Sexy Community -- t5. Sexual Racism -- t6. New, Now, Next, Not -- tMidnight -- t7. Gay Disneyland -- t8. Becoming Gay -- t9. One of the Good Gays -- t10. Straight to Halsted -- t11. Girlstown -- t12. Take Back Boystown -- t13. Queer Is Community -- t14. Dawn -- tAcknowledgments -- tSupplement: Producing Ethnography -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom neighborhoods as large as Chelsea or the Castro, to locales limited to a single club, like The Shamrock in Madison or Sidewinders in Albuquerque, gay areas are becoming normal. Straight people flood in. Gay people flee out. Scholars call this transformation assimilation, and some argue that we—gay and straight alike—are becoming “post-gay.” Jason Orne argues that rather than post-gay, America is becoming “post-queer,” losing the radical lessons of sex. In Boystown, Orne takes readers on a detailed, lively journey through Chicago’s Boystown, which serves as a model for gayborhoods around the country. The neighborhood, he argues, has become an entertainment district—a gay Disneyland—where people get lost in the magic of the night and where straight white women can “go on safari.” In their original form, though, gayborhoods like this one don’t celebrate differences; they create them. By fostering a space outside the mainstream, gay spaces allow people to develop an alternative culture—a queer culture that celebrates sex. Orne spent three years doing fieldwork in Boystown, searching for ways to ask new questions about the connective power of sex and about what it means to be not just gay, but queer. The result is the striking Boystown, illustrated throughout with street photography by Dylan Stuckey. In the dark backrooms of raunchy clubs where bachelorettes wouldn’t dare tread, people are hooking up and forging “naked intimacy.” Orne is your tour guide to the real Boystown, then, where sex functions as a vital center and an antidote to assimilation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aGay barsxSocial aspectszIllinoiszChicago. 0aGay communityzIllinoiszChicago. 0aGay culturezIllinoiszChicago. 0aGay culture. 0aGay menzIllinoiszChicagoxSocial life and customs. 0aSexxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aStuckey, Dylan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226413426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226413426.jpg  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles